{"id":"2211.03737","submitter":"Hae-Young Kee","authors":"Xiaoyu Liu and Hae-Young Kee","title":"Non-Kitaev vs. Kitaev Honeycomb Cobaltates","comments":"10 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.107.054420","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  Recently, honeycomb cobaltates with 3$d^7$ were proposed to display Kitaev\nphysics despite weak spin-orbit coupling. However, other theoretical and\nexperimental works found leading XXZ Heisenberg and negligible Kitaev\ninteractions in BaCo$_2$(AsO$_4$)$_2$ (BCAO), which calls for a further study\nto clarify the origin of the discrepancies. Here we derive the analytical\nexpressions of the spin model using strong-coupling perturbation theory. With\ntight binding parameters obtained by {\\it ab-initio} calculations for idealized\nhoneycomb BCAO, we find that the largest intraorbital $t_{2g}-t_{2g}$ exchange\npath, which was assumed to be small in the earlier theory proposal, leads to a\nferromagnetic (FM) Heisenberg interaction. This becomes the dominant\ninteraction, as other $t_{2g}-e_g$ and $e_g-e_g$ contributions almost cancel\neach other. Exactly the same assumed-to-be-small channel also generates an\nantiferromagnetic Kitaev interaction, which then cancels a FM Kitaev\ninteraction from $t_{2g}-e_g$ paths, resulting in a small Kitaev interaction.\nUnder the trigonal distortion, the preeminent isotropic Heisenberg becomes an\nanisotropic XXZ model as expected, which is the case for BCAO. However, in\nNa$_3$Co$_2$SbO$_6$ the intraorbital $t_{2g}-t_{2g}$ hopping is smaller and\ncomparable to the $t_{2g}-e_g$ hopping, leading to a delicate competition\nbetween enhanced Kitaev and reduced Heisenberg interactions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Nov 2022 18:11:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 12 Nov 2022 02:34:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-01"}
